Row filters.

A row filter is a function that returns a boolean for each row. Unity catalog adds an implicit where clause on every read against the table, keeping only the rows where the function returns true for the querying principal.

So you might write a region filter — a function that, for a compliance analyst in India, returns true only when the country is India; for a compliance analyst in the U-S, true only for U-S rows; and for the global compliance group, true for everything. You attach it to the table with an alter-table set-row-filter statement, naming the column it reads.

After that, every select from the table is implicitly filtered, and each principal sees only their slice. To remove it, you alter the table and drop the row filter.

And here's the powerful combination — a row filter plus a column mask together give you the bank's full sensitive-data regime. A compliance analyst in India sees full data, but only for Indian customers. A plain analyst sees only the Indian rows and also gets the card number redacted. Two features, composed on the base table, enforce the whole policy.
